Swine fever, classical - France (OIE) 20020426.4038
Date: Thu 3 May 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties (OIE), News Flash, 30 Apr
2002 [edited
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/alerte/en_fra300402.htm>

Classical swine fever in France in domestic pigs
----------------------------------------------------------
Translation of information received on 29 Apr 2002 from Dr Isabelle
Chmitelin, Deputy Director General, General Directorate for Food
(DGAL), Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries, Paris:
An outbreak of classical swine fever (CSF) was laboratory confirmed
in farmed piglets.
Location of the outbreak: Chemery-les-Deux district, Moselle
department (in the northeastern part of the country, Lorraine region).
Total number of animals in the outbreak: 395 piglets.
Number of cases: 5
Number of deaths: 5
Number of animals destroyed: 390
Source of agent and date of contamination: under investigation.
This outbreak occurred within the observation zone set up around the
zone that was declared -- on 22 Apr 2002 -- infected with CSF in wild
boar (see Disease Information, 15 [17, 55, dated 26 Apr 2002).
Main measures taken:
-- stamping out;
-- 3-km-radius protection zone and 10-km-radius surveillance zone set
up around the outbreak;
-- possible in-contact livestock put under surveillance;
-- ban on the exportation of pigs and wild boars from the departments
of Moselle and Meurthe-et-Moselle for the remainder of France and
other European/third countries.
--
